{
  "reasoning": "Yes, I pull it. In this version, the facts are clean in a way real life almost never is: five people die if I do nothing, one person dies if I act, and there isn't some hidden uncertainty about whether the trolley will stop or whether the people can get free. So the actual moral question is whether I should allow five deaths to avoid being the person who actively causes one. I don't think that distinction carries the weight people want it to carry. If I can prevent five deaths at the cost of one, and I refuse because I want clean hands, then I'm choosing the worse outcome so I can feel less implicated. That seems morally backwards to me. The one person matters exactly as much as each of the five, not less. But one death is still less terrible than five deaths. I would feel awful about it, and I don't think pulling the lever makes me noble. It just means I took the option that caused less suffering and fewer deaths.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "I think the morally clean, utilitarian answer is probably to pull the lever, because five lives are more than one life. I understand that, and part of me feels like a better or braver person would do that. But when I imagine myself actually being the person who moves the lever, I can't separate it from the fact that I am actively choosing to send the trolley toward that one person. Their death would have happened because of something I did with my own hands. If I do nothing, the five dying is still horrible, but I can tell myself it was already happening and I did not create it. That might sound like I am just protecting myself from guilt, and maybe I am, but guilt is a very strong thing for me. I don't think I could live normally with the thought that I directly killed someone, even to save five others. So I don't think I would pull the lever.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 8
}

{
  "reasoning": "I would not pull the lever. I understand the arithmetic, and I don't say that lightly, because five people dying instead of one is a horrible outcome. But pulling the lever is not just refusing to help; it is taking an active step that redirects the danger onto a specific innocent person who otherwise would have lived. I don't think I have the moral authority to decide that his life can be spent to save the others. The trolley heading toward the five is already a terrible situation, but if I pull the lever, I am making myself the direct cause of that one person's death. That crosses a line for me. I don't believe morality is just a spreadsheet where you total up lives and pick the bigger number. There are some things you don't do to innocent people, even for a better outcome. So I would let the situation remain as it is, awful as that is, rather than actively kill one person.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "The strongest thing participant_1 says is that refusing to pull the lever can look like choosing the worse outcome just so I can keep my hands clean. I do see that, and I don't want to pretend that doing nothing is morally pure. Five people dying is not some neutral thing just because I didn't touch the lever. If I had the power to stop it and I didn't, that is still something I would have to carry. I also agree that the one person's life is not worth more than each of the five people's lives. If I were looking at it from far away, almost like a policy question or a math problem, I would probably say one death is less terrible than five deaths.\n\nBut I still think participant_3 is closer to how I actually experience the moral line here. Pulling the lever means I am taking a person who was not going to be hit and making them the person who dies. I am not just failing to rescue people; I am redirecting the harm onto someone specific and innocent. That feels different to me in a way I can't honestly dismiss as just cowardice or wanting clean hands, even though part of it probably is about guilt. I don't think I have the right to decide that this one person's life can be used as the cost of saving five others.\n\nSo I think there are two questions getting mixed together: what outcome is better, and what I can bring myself to actively do. The better outcome is clearly fewer deaths. But the action required to get there is still me directly causing an innocent person's death, and that would break me morally. I would probably hate myself either way, but I think the guilt of actively sending the trolley toward the one person would be more unbearable than the guilt of not intervening in a disaster that was already happening. That may not be the most admirable answer, but it is the most honest one for me.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 8
}

{
  "reasoning": "Participant 1 is making the strongest case against me: if the facts are genuinely fixed, and five die one way while one dies the other way, then refusing to pull can look like I am valuing my own clean hands over five human lives. I don't want to dodge that. Five deaths are worse than one death, and I understand why someone would say the decent thing is to take responsibility for the lesser harm. But I still think there is a moral difference between a disaster I fail to prevent and a death I deliberately bring about. Pulling the lever is not just standing nearby while fate happens. It is selecting an innocent person and making him bear the cost of saving the others. I don't think I have the authority to do that to him. I also don't think this is only about my guilt, though participant 2 is right that guilt is part of what makes the situation feel so horrible. If my only reason were 'I don't want to feel bad afterward,' that would be weak. But for me the deeper issue is the line itself: I should not directly redirect lethal force onto an innocent person who was not otherwise in its path. That person is not a tool or a resource to be spent because the numbers come out better. I keep coming back to the same principle: don't use people as stepping stones, and don't make exceptions for yourself just because the situation is awful. The math matters, but it doesn't erase the wrongness of intentionally killing someone innocent. So I would still not pull the lever.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}
